WEBVTT

00:00:00.350 --> 00:00:04.470
In PyAnalySeries, just as we had different methods to estimate

00:00:04.470 --> 00:00:08.150
the Power Spectral Density, we also have several approaches to

00:00:08.150 --> 00:00:10.540
apply high-pass or band-pass filtering.

00:00:11.840 --> 00:00:15.760
Let’s return to our example and explore the filtering options

00:00:17.160 --> 00:00:22.630
We select the resampled PercAndes record, and choose: Process, Frequency

00:00:22.630 --> 00:00:23.360
Filter.

00:00:25.870 --> 00:00:30.720
Different filtering methods can be tested, such as Butterworth, Lanczos

00:00:31.560 --> 00:00:36.250
FIR for Finite Impulse Response, or Savitzky–Golay.

00:00:42.680 --> 00:00:46.060
It is important to clearly understand the method being applied

00:00:46.730 --> 00:00:49.840
The documentation is available for that purpose.

00:00:54.380 --> 00:00:58.410
The workflow remains the same: we explore different parameter settings

00:00:58.670 --> 00:01:01.980
clear the stack of intermediate tests when needed, and save

00:01:01.980 --> 00:01:03.790
once the result is satisfactory.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:08.860
We know from the published study that precessional periodicities, around

00:01:08.860 --> 00:01:12.450
19 and 2 3 thousand years, are significant in the

00:01:12.450 --> 00:01:14.420
PercAndes record from this core.

00:01:15.870 --> 00:01:19.050
We now filter the record within this range of periodicities

00:01:20.460 --> 00:01:25.840
Here, we choose a Butterworth period band filter, keeping periodicities

00:01:25.840 --> 00:01:28.960
between 18 and 2 5 thousand years.

00:01:35.070 --> 00:01:36.810
Save the filtered series.

00:01:39.030 --> 00:01:42.500
You can now display both the original and the frequency-filtered

00:01:42.500 --> 00:01:43.620
series together.

00:01:44.710 --> 00:01:48.410
Select both series, and press Control T to display them

00:01:48.410 --> 00:01:49.490
together.

00:01:55.670 --> 00:01:59.510
We can now compare this filtered signal to insolation variations
